                <opener>
                    <dateline>Aug. 17, 1971</dateline> 
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>5835 Vine St.</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebr. 68505</addrLine> 
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>What a wonderful letter full of good news. It is great that your work is coming into its own and that you are also getting <hi rend="caps">PAID</hi> for it. I couldn't be more delighted.</p>
                
                <p>I am so glad about your youth section of the autobiography being all accepted and scheduled for print. I look forward to it with great anticipation.</p>
                
                <p>Three cheers for the Dick Cavett show. It was great. I saw it and wished I could see it again. I know it created a lot of interest and stimulated inquiries that should have done a lot for the books.</p>
                
                <p>We are looking forward to seeing you on Oct. 9. Plans for the meeting haven't fully materialized yet--at least they haven't forwarded them to me. I am to be the coordinator for meals, rooms and so on here in Red Cloud. Will you and the Youngs and Jacquot be staying over night?</p> 
                
                <p>I am feeling really fine and am recovering faster than the doctors thought possible. It is good to have escaped the shadow of death.</p> 
                
                <p>I had such a good visit with Stan and I am glad he was at Bancroft. I am going to make it to one of those meetings one of these days. This year was impossible.</p>
                
                <p>I'm glad the work on the rest of the autobiography is going along. It's great that you can do so much and find such stimulating success in your later years. You deserve all the good that comes to you, and the world is lucky to have you.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately,</salute> 
                
                    <signed>Mildred</signed> 
                    <signed>Mildred R. Bennett</signed>
                </closer>
                
